We came to South Greenland in part to sail among Icebergs. This is one of the most remarkable ones we saw on our trip. For a moment we thought about driving the boat through the arch to get a closer look at it but the captain quickly deterred us from it from fears of it collapsing on us.. What a beast

The Greenland ice sheet. This is a panorama of 12 horizontal photos, just to give you a sense of the scale of this place. Just a few years ago, the ice fell into the water but in you can see that it is retracting over the rock now and will continue to do until its no longer visible from the sea. Powerful seeing our changing climate first hand..
Finally got around editing one of my favourite photos from the Greenland trip. This is Sebastien, our rad skipper from France on the @auroraarktika, taking the crew back to the boat..
Light in the valley

A place to breathe. A place to swim. A place to fish. A place to lie in the sun... What I love about the outside is that everyone choses what to do in it, and doing nothing at all is also an option. 
#EOS3
Walking back to camp through the endless larch forest. Always neat spending time with people whose idea of a camping trip is waking up before sunrise to go somewhere high to watch the sun go up..

A few nights ago from the summit of Lincoln Peak. The temps were in the single digits, a cold breeze from the north east was blowing as we waited for sunset. No luck. A band of clouds to the west was blocking the sun. Pretty typical this time of the year out here. We packed up and as we turned around to head down we got treated to this ball of fire...
In the shadow of Great Northern. Never thought I‚Äôd be able to witness this a few minutes from the house..
